 of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Blakeland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Lawkland (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lackland","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Durham): topographic name from Lawkland in Yorkshire. The placename derives from Old Norse <i>laukr</i> ‘leek’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Blakeland VI was born in 1265, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, his father, Sir Robert de Blakeland V, was 23 and his mother, Lady Agnes Buckland, was 23. He married Agnes De Blakeland in 1285, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1286, in his hometown, at the age of 21, and was buried in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1265–1286":"1265–1286","1270–1365":"1270–1365","1286–1366":"1286–1366","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1242–1303":"1242–1303","1259":"1259